Male genitalia (
Fig. 67
). Uncus long (
1.2 – 1.35 mm
), valva elongate, with small subapical ventral lobe, slerotized long and stout harpe curved towards the costa and here again curved towards base of valva, with spinose, rounded tip. Aedeagus comparatively short (2.0 – 2.1 mm ), straight, stalk very short, with two lateral sclerites and small subapical, lateral tooth. Sternum A 8 without lobes or projections.

Female genitalia (
Fig. 96
). Sterigma triangular, edges rounded. Ductus bursae comparatively long (2.0 mm), broad, sclerotized. Corpus bursae globular, signum small with two posterior teeth.

Etymology. The name refers to the distribution area north of the distribution area of the sister species (
P. croca
); latin septentrionalis = northern.
